## What this measures (self-contained — no other docs needed)

The **W0→W4 decomposition ladder**: one durable transaction, adding one data
model at a time, so the multi-model write tax is read by subtraction. Every
commit is one group-coalesced `F_FULLFSYNC` (matched durability). The number
reported is **marginal ms per durable commit** at each pre-grown table size
(`MM_SAMPLE=200` commits averaged; pre-grow not timed).

| Rung | What the single transaction does |
|------|----------------------------------|
| **W0** | plain relational row INSERT (WAL + heap + fsync) |
| **W1** | W0 + a B-tree secondary index entry |
| **W2** | W1 + a `VECTOR(128)` value + its ANN index (HNSW) |
| **W3** | W2 + a graph edge + adjacency-index maintenance |
| **W4** | W3 + event-queue capture — **the full four-model commit** |

`W4−W0` is the total multi-model tax; `W4/W0` is the multiplier. The thesis:
one shared fsync makes W4 ≈ W0 (not N×), and it should stay that way as rows
grow. A rising `W4/W0` means per-model index CPU (esp. HNSW) is eroding it.

## Table 1 — Multi-model commit cost vs table size (ms/commit)

| rows | W0 | W1 | W2 | W3 | W4 | W4−W0 | W4/W0 |
|-----:|---:|---:|---:|---:|---:|------:|------:|
| 1000 | 3.13 | 3.98 | 3.94 | 4.03 | 3.98 | 0.84 | 1.27× |

## Table 2 — Per-model marginal maintenance vs size (ms added per commit)

| rows | Δ btree (W1−W0) | Δ vector (W2−W1) | Δ edge (W3−W2) | Δ event (W4−W3) |
|-----:|----------------:|-----------------:|---------------:|----------------:|
| 1000 | +0.85 | -0.04 | +0.09 | -0.06 |

*(small-size deltas are near-noise — every rung sits within a few hundred µs
of the fsync floor; the vector column is the one expected to separate as rows
grow, since HNSW insert is O(log n) distance computations.)*

## Table 3 — CRUD stress: unidb (SQL) vs Postgres (relational)

Full CRUD at matched durability — not just INSERT: bulk insert, filtered and
grouped SELECT, bulk UPDATE, selected and full DELETE. Each row shows how many
records the operation touched and its throughput (records/sec). Table pre-loaded
to **20000 rows** (`MM_CRUD_ROWS` to change).

**Note on INSERT:** here each row is its **own durable commit** (one fsync/row —
the per-row latency floor, ~hundreds/sec), which is why it is far below the
batched bulk-load path in Table 3.1 (one commit per 5000 rows).

_Durability lens: unidb `F_FULLFSYNC`, Postgres `wal_sync_method=fsync_writethrough` (matched)._

Extra columns (C1, unidb only): **WAL B/row** = cumulative WAL bytes the op
appended ÷ records touched (the index-maintenance proof — a `body`-only UPDATE
should append ~0 index bytes once unchanged indexed columns are skipped);
**dec/row** = full-row heap decodes ÷ records touched (exposes full-scan waste
on the write path — a selective op that decodes every row shows dec/row ≫ 1).

| operation | records | unidb (rec/s) | postgres (rec/s) | unidb ÷ PG | remark (winner · margin) | WAL B/row | dec/row |
|-----------|--------:|--------------:|-----------------:|-----------:|:-------------------------|----------:|--------:|
| INSERT (per-row commit) | 20000 | 302 | 309 | 0.98× | **postgres** +2% | 8833 | 0.00 |
| SELECT filtered (k<N) | 20000 | 266519 | 1958920 | 0.14× | **postgres** +635% | 0 | 2.00 |
| SELECT grouped (GROUP BY g) | 40000 | 4350999 | 5480766 | 0.79× | **postgres** +26% | 0 | 1.00 |
| UPDATE bulk (k<N/2) | 10000 | 34833 | 306998 | 0.11× | **postgres** +781% | 8868 | 4.00 |
| DELETE selected (k>=N) | 20000 | 300594 | 1323218 | 0.23× | **postgres** +340% | 230 | 2.00 |
| DELETE all | 20000 | 301871 | 1517815 | 0.20× | **postgres** +403% | 231 | 1.00 |

## Table 3.1 — Bulk stress: insert + full-scan select at scale

Scaling behaviour of a single-table load and a full-table scan as the row count
climbs. For each size a **fresh** table is built, `n` rows are bulk-inserted
(batched prepared single-row inserts, one durable commit per 5000
rows — the same method on both engines), then a full-**heap** scan is timed
(`COUNT(*) WHERE body <> 'x'` — a predicate on the non-indexed `body` column, so
neither engine can serve it index-only; this measures real scan throughput, not a
count optimizer). Throughput is records/sec. Sizes swept: `[10000]` (`MM_BULK_SIZES`
to override — e.g. push to `5000000` or `10000000` for a heavier run). The default
tops out at 2M to keep a full report reasonable; the engine handles ≥10M.

**On the scan gap at scale:** Postgres runs a **parallel** sequential scan (multiple
worker processes) once the table crosses its parallel threshold, while unidb scans
**single-threaded**; so a large scan-side lead is Postgres's parallel-query capability,
not a per-row storage-speed difference (at small sizes, below PG's threshold, the two
are much closer).

_Durability lens: unidb `F_FULLFSYNC`, Postgres `wal_sync_method=fsync_writethrough` (matched)._

| rows | unidb insert (rec/s) | postgres insert (rec/s) | insert winner · margin | unidb scan (rec/s) | postgres scan (rec/s) | scan winner · margin |
|-----:|---------------------:|------------------------:|:-----------------------|-------------------:|----------------------:|:---------------------|
| 10000 | 36129 | 28741 | **unidb** +26% | 5884084 | 12859669 | **postgres** +119% |

## Table 4 — unidb multi-model (1 txn) vs Postgres relational, at scale

unidb commits **four model-writes in one transaction** (relational + `VECTOR(128)`
+ graph edge + event); Postgres does the **relational INSERT only** (1 model-write)
— by design ("not its boat"). Swept across tx counts (`MM_TX_SWEEP`) to see whether
the multi-model cost stays flat or the synchronous HNSW index erodes it at scale.

**How to read this table.** A *commit* is one durable transaction — one `fsync` at
commit — and the rate is transactions/sec (single writer, so no group-commit
coalescing). Each **unidb** transaction does **4× the work** of a **Postgres** one
(`model-writes/txn` = 4 vs 1), and one of those four is an expensive HNSW vector
insert. So `unidb ÷ PG < 1` is **expected** — it is the price of folding four models
into a single atomic, crash-consistent commit, not a slowdown on equal work. If you
only need the relational write, Postgres is faster; the multi-model commit is what
Postgres-relational alone cannot do at all.

_Durability lens: unidb `F_FULLFSYNC`, Postgres `wal_sync_method=fsync_writethrough` (matched)._

| txns | model-writes/txn | unidb txns/s | unidb ms/txn | postgres txns/s | postgres ms/txn | unidb ÷ PG |
|-----:|:----------------:|-------------:|-------------:|----------------:|----------------:|-----------:|
| 1000 | 4 : 1 | 265 | 3.772 | 313 | 3.190 | 0.85× |
